-**Defining architecture — build-time snapshot (Shopify-style), NOT runtime fetch.**
-`scripts/snapshot.ts` reads all catalogue data from Supabase at build time (with
-the service key) and writes `src/data/catalog.json`, bundled into the site. The
-storefront reads that JSON synchronously — **zero DB reads while browsing**.
-Supabase is touched at runtime **only for writes**: order insert (via the
-`create_order` RPC) and inquiry insert. Admin edits → click **Publish** →
-Vercel Deploy Hook rebuilds with a fresh snapshot (~1 min).
+**Architecture, updated by PR #3 — snapshot seeds, live fetch overrides.**
+`scripts/snapshot.ts` still reads all catalogue data from Supabase at build time
+and writes `src/data/catalog.json`, bundled into the site — this is what SSR/
+prerender use and what powers instant first paint. But as of PR #3,
+`CatalogProvider` (`src/contexts/CatalogContext.tsx`) refetches the catalogue
+**live** from Supabase in the browser on mount via `src/lib/liveCatalog.ts`
+(same camelCase output shape as the snapshot) and swaps it in once loaded — so
+admin add/edit/delete now shows up on the **next page load**, not just after a
+Publish/rebuild. If the live fetch fails, the seed snapshot stays (fail-safe).
+The **Publish button / deploy hook still matters** for SEO (prerendered HTML)
+and as the fail-safe seed, so it isn't obsolete — just no longer the only path
+to freshness for logged-in browsing.
+**Two parallel mapping paths to keep in sync**: `scripts/snapshot.ts` (build)
+and `src/lib/liveCatalog.ts` (runtime) both transform the same DB rows into
+`Catalog` shape — any new catalogue column needs both updated, plus
+`scripts/seed-data.ts` (offline fallback) and `types/catalog.ts`.
 
